Impact of Tourism on Income in North Carolina

Introduction

In this project, I will explore the relationship between tourism and income in North Carolina. As someone from a tourism-heavy county, I have heard various "takes" from different people - some who say that tourism raises income in our county and others who disagree. I wanted to use this project as an opportunity to explore what the facts behind that relationship are. In order to do this, I found data on the expected income of children who were born in a certain county and remained there into adulthood and compared this across North Carolina. This allows for a strict comparison of the individual counties without mobilization as a factor. Then, I compared this income data to data regarding tourism by county in NC. I decided to limit my analysis to purely North Carolina for two reasons. First, it is the only state whose tourism geography I know much about and would therefore be able to contextualize any outlying results. Second, it narrows the scope which in turn allows for more depth. Despite this, I suspect that the findings of this project likely has implications beyond North Carolina as well.

My data is from 4 locations. First, Opportunity Atlas (https://www.opportunityatlas.org/) is where I recieved data on expected income for children who remain in their counties. Their data additionally breaks down this expected income further into racial groups, gender, and parental income, of which only the latter was used. I am not aware of any specific analyses constructed off of this data but it is incredibly insightful into different geographical trends across the United States. Second, I used Visit NC (https://partners.visitnc.com/contents/sdownload/73486/file/2022+County+Level+Visitor+Expenditures.pdf) to find tourism data for each county. This data has been referenced in presentations at symposiums that I have attended regarding the impact of tourism in North Carolina, although I do not have a link or access to those presentations to provide here. Third, I used the North Carolina Association of County Commissioners (https://www.ncacc.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/2024_02_County-GDP.pdf) to find the GDP of each North Carolina county, which is used in the analysis. This data was manually inputted into in an excel document by me in combination with the VisitNC data. Finally, I used a geojson file from NCOneMap (https://www.nconemap.gov/datasets/NCEM-GIS::north-carolina-state-and-county-boundary-polygons/explore) in order to create the maps shown throughout the project. Similar to Opportunity Atlas, I don't know of any specific analysis done with either the NCACC or the NCOneMap data, however they are both quite useful and appear to be the most reliable data on their respective topics.

Data wrangling: Importing Files, Creating and Merging Dataframes, Calculating Tourism as % of GDP, Finding Logs.

In order to clean and organize this data, the following steps were performed:

  • The three files were read and saved as Panda's DataFrames or GeoDataFrames.
  • Certain relevant columns within those files were selected for and inserted into new dataframes.
  • Columns with complex names were renamed using a dictionary to increase accessibility.
  • A calculation was performed to find Tourism as a percent of each county's GDP
  • These new dataframes were joined with one another to make larger and more useful dataframes for further analysis.
  • Log calculations were performed and saved as columns to be used in linear regression calculations.

These maps help to visualize certain economic trends within North Carolina. In the top two maps, it appears as though total tourist expenditures are correlated with the GDP of a county, with a few exceptions. However, if you analyze tourist expenditures as a percent of GDP, as is done in the bottom left map, that relationship disappears: in raw percentage terms, the Western and Coastal NorthEast regions attribute a greater portion of their economy to tourism than do the economically larger regions (Charlotte, The Triangle, and the Triad). This trend further continues once you normalize the percentages by taking the log of tourism as a percent of GDP. Here, the normalization allows for a greater color contrast between counties with low and high percents of their GDP attributed to tourism. These regional trends perpetuate in this bottom right map, with Western and Coastal Carolina drastically differing from other regions - with some exception like Moore County of the Sandhills region, which notably holds the US Open annually.

So far in our data, there appears to be a dynamic where Western and Coastal NorthEast North Carolina appear to have higher expected incomes for the lowest percentiles and simultaneously have a larger share of their economy be due to tourism, suggesting that higher levels of tourism relative to the local economy might be correlated with a higher expected income for these people. In this next section, we will examine the statistical validity of this potential relationship via linear regressions.

These are scatterplots that show how the 4 percentile groups's log expected income relates to the log of Tourism as a percent of county GDP wherein each individual dot represents one of NC's 100 counties. The line overlaid in each plot is the Ordinary Least Squares regression of that plot, which represents the line with the lowest amount of total error possible that has a constant slope. In these regressions, it appears that the trends anticipated by the maps hold true: that an increase in log tourism as percent of GDP appears to be associated with an increase of log expected income for the lowest percentiles while it is associated with a decrease in log tourism for the highest percentiles. Therefore, if one's goal were to increase the income of the bottom percentile, increasing dependence on tourism might be effective.

Analyses: Learning More Via Regression Statistics

The regression scatterplots showed some relationships between log tourism as percent of GDP and log expected income. Let's analyze how statistically significant those relationships are.

In[43]:
# Create a new dataframe for the regression with relevant columns.
regression_data_1st = NC_complete[["logT-G", "logfirst"]]
# Extract the independent (X) and dependent (Y) variables
X_1st = regression_data_1st["logT-G"]
Y_1st = regression_data_1st["logfirst"]
# Add a Constant to the Independent Variable
X_1st = sm.add_constant(X_1st) 
# Fit the Regression Model
model_1st = sm.OLS(Y_1st, X_1st)  # Ordinary Least Squares regression
results_1st = model_1st.fit()
# Print the results
print(results_1st.summary())

Here, this regression shows multiple things. First, the F-statistic and the adjusted R-squared point to the fact that, within the 1st percentile group, increases in log tourism as percent of GDP correlate with increases in log expected income to a statistically significant degree. Specifically, that variation in log tourism as percent of GDP account for 20.8% of adjusted variation in expected income. Given that there are a significant amount of potential factors that would go into expected income, this is a significant percentage. The coefficient of logT-G means that as tourism as percent of GDP increases by 1%, expected income of children of the bottom percentile increases by 0.1%. In no other percentile category did the regression between log tourism as percent of GDP and log expected income show a statistically significant relationship, which was expected given the data visualizations. These can be found in the appendix.

Conclusions

In conclusion, this data analysis has shown multiple facts about North Carolina. First, that there is a significant geographical disparity between how child expected income in different counties perform for various parental income percentiles. Certain places in Western and Coastal North Carolina particularly overperform in the lower percentiles. We also showed that these same regions have a disproportionately high percentage of their GDP that are attributed to tourism. Then, the specific relationship between tourism and child expected income was more closely examined by means of a linear regression. This found no significant relationship for any group except the first percentile, which demonstrated a positive relationship between log expected income and log tourism expenditure as percent of GDP.

These address the question of interest in a straightforward manner. I wanted to explore how the tourism industry impacts the expected wages of those who live in and are from the counties that tourism affects. It was shown that tourism has a positive economic effect on those with parents at the bottom of the income distribution while there is little to no statistically significant effect for those from higher income families. This provides evidence to the argument that tourism is a positive thing for North Carolinian society.

For the future, I think this research could be expanded upon to each county in the United States to provide a more national view of how tourism impacts different classes in our society. But even within North Carolina, I think that breaking the data down even further into not only how tourism affects expected income based on parental income but also on race and gender would be incredibly worthwile as well, given that the tourism and hospitality sectors are traditionally disproportionately female, it could be interesting to see whether or not women economically benefit from increased tourism more than men - or vice versa.

NC_complete.reset_index()
NC_complete_geo = NC_geo.join(NC_complete)

# Add a Constant to the
